{"id": "m01", "question": "What is the first-line treatment for community-acquired pneumonia in adults?", "ground_truth": "For previously healthy outpatients, a macrolide (e.g. azithromycin) or doxycycline; for patients with comorbidities or recent antibiotics, a respiratory fluoroquinolone or a beta-lactam plus a macrolide.", "type": "factual", "smoke": true}
{"id": "m02", "question": "What is the management of diabetic ketoacidosis?", "ground_truth": "IV fluids (isotonic saline), insulin infusion, and electrolyte correction (especially potassium), with close monitoring of glucose, anion gap, and ketones; treat the precipitating cause.", "type": "factual", "smoke": true}
{"id": "m03", "question": "What is a first-line antihypertensive for a patient with diabetes?", "ground_truth": "An ACE inhibitor or angiotensin receptor blocker (ARB) is preferred in patients with diabetes, particularly with albuminuria, for renal protection.", "type": "factual", "smoke": true}
{"id": "m04", "question": "Compare the typical presentations of bacterial versus viral meningitis.", "ground_truth": "Bacterial meningitis typically presents with rapid onset of high fever, severe headache, neck stiffness, and altered mental status, with CSF showing neutrophilic pleocytosis, high protein, low glucose; viral (aseptic) meningitis is usually milder with lymphocytic CSF, normal glucose.", "type": "synthesis", "smoke": false}
